==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trade
<hw>Trade</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly, a path, OE.
<ets>tred</ets> a footmark. See <er>Tread</er>, <pos>n.</pos> &
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A track; a trail; a way; a path;
also, passage; travel; resort.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A postern with a blind wicket there was,⟦br⟧
A common <qex>trade</qex> to pass through Priam's house.</q>
<rj><qau>Surrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hath tracted forth some salvage beastes <qex>trade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or, I'll be buried in the king's highway,⟦br⟧
Some way of common <qex>trade</qex>, where subjects' feet⟦br⟧
May hourly trample on their sovereign's head.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Course; custom; practice; occupation;
employment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The right <xex>trade</xex>
of religion.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Udall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There those five sisters had continual <qex>trade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Long did I love this lady,⟦br⟧
Long was my travel, long my <qex>trade</qex> to win her.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy sin's not accidental but a <qex>trade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Business of any kind; matter of mutual
consideration; affair; dealing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have you any further <qex>trade</qex> with us?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Specifically: The act or business of exchanging
commodities by barter, or by buying and selling for money; commerce;
traffic; barter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Trade comprehends every species of exchange or dealing,
either in the produce of land, in manufactures, in bills, or in money;
but it is chiefly used to denote the barter or purchase and sale of
goods, wares, and merchandise, either by wholesale or retail. Trade is
either <xex>foreign</xex> or <xex>domestic</xex>. <xex>Foreign</xex>
trade consists in the exportation and importation of goods, or the
exchange of the commodities of different countries. <xex>Domestic</xex>,
or <xex>home</xex>, trade is the exchange, or buying and selling, of
goods within a country. Trade is also by the <xex>wholesale</xex>, that
is, by the package or in large quantities, generally to be sold again,
or it is by <xex>retail</xex>, or in small parcels. The
<xex>carrying</xex> trade is the business of transporting commodities
from one country to another, or between places in the same country, by
land or water.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The business which a person has learned, and which
he engages in, for procuring subsistence, or for profit; occupation;
especially, mechanical employment as distinguished from the liberal
arts, the learned professions, and agriculture; <as>as, we speak of the
<ex>trade</ex> of a smith, of a carpenter, or mason, but not now of the
<ex>trade</ex> of a farmer, or a lawyer, or a physician</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Accursed usury was all his <qex>trade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The homely, slighted, shepherd's <qex>trade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will instruct thee in my <qex>trade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Instruments of any occupation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The house and household goods, his <qex>trade</qex> of war.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A company of men engaged in the same occupation;
thus, booksellers and publishers speak of the customs of the
<xex>trade</xex>, and are collectively designated as <xex>the
trade</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The trade winds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Refuse or rubbish from a mine.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Profession; occupation; office; calling;
avocation; employment; commerce; dealing; traffic.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Board of trade</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Board</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Trade dollar</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Dollar</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Trade price</b></col>, <cd>the price at
which goods are sold to members of the same trade, or by wholesale
dealers to retailers.</cd> -- <col><b>Trade sale</b></col>, <cd>an
auction by and for the trade, especially that of the booksellers.</cd>
-- <col><b>Trade wind</b></col>, <cd>a wind in the torrid zone, and
often a little beyond at, which blows from the same quarter throughout
the year, except when affected by local causes; -- so called because of
its usefulness to navigators, and hence to trade.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The general direction of the trade winds is from N. E.
to S. W. on the north side of the equator, and from S. E. to N. W. on
the south side of the equator. They are produced by the joint effect of
the rotation of the earth and the movement of the air from the polar
toward the equatorial regions, to supply the vacancy caused by heating,
rarefaction, and consequent ascent of the air in the latter regions. The
trade winds are principally limited to two belts in the tropical
regions, one on each side of the equator, and separated by a belt which
is characterized by calms or variable weather.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trade
<hw>Trade</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Traded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To barter, or to buy
and sell; to be engaged in the exchange, purchase, or sale of goods,
wares, merchandise, or anything else; to traffic; to bargain; to carry
on commerce as a business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A free port, where nations . . . resorted with their goods and
<qex>traded</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To buy and sell or exchange property in a single
instance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To have dealings; to be concerned or associated; --
usually followed by <xex>with</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How did you dare to <qex>trade</qex> and traffic with Macbeth?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trade
<hw>Trade</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To sell or exchange in commerce;
to barter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>traded</qex> the persons of men.</q> <rj><qau>Ezek.
xxvii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To dicker and to swop, to <qex>trade</qex> rifles and watches.</q>
<rj><qau>Cooper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trade</ent>⟦br⟧

